# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cratedb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] Lucene has been ported to other programming languages including Object Pascal, Perl, C#, C++, Python, Ruby and PHP.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] Doug Cutting originally wrote Lucene in 1999.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] He had previously written two while at Xerox PARC, one at Apple, and a fourth at Excite.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] It was initially available for download from its home at the SourceForge web site.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] It joined the Apache Software Foundation's Jakarta family of open-source Java products in September 2001 and became its own top-level Apache project in February 2005.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] The name Lucene is Doug Cutting's wife's middle name and her maternal grandmother's first name.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] Lucene formerly included a number of sub-projects, such as Lucene.NET, Mahout, Tika and Nutch.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] These three are now independent top-level projects.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] In March 2010, the Apache Solr search server joined as a Lucene sub-project, merging the developer communities.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] Version 4.0 was released on October 12, 2012.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] In March 2021, Lucene changed its logo, and Apache Solr became a top level Apache project again, independent from Lucene.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] While suitable for any application that requires full text indexing and searching capability, Lucene is recognized for its utility in the implementation of Internet search engines and local, single-site searching.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] Lucene includes a feature to perform a fuzzy search based on edit distance.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] Lucene has also been used to implement recommendation systems.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] For example, Lucene's 'MoreLikeThis' Class can generate recommendations for similar documents.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] In contrast, citation-based document similarity measures tended to be more suitable for recommending more broadly related documents, meaning citation-based approaches may be more suitable for generating serendipitous recommendations, as long as documents to be recommended contain in-text citations.
[src:cratedb/apache-lucene] Lucene itself is just an indexing and search library and does not contain crawling and HTML parsing functionality.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] Help us improve CrateDB by taking our User Survey!
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] CrateDB is a distributed SQL database that makes it simple to store and analyze massive amounts of data in real-time.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] CrateDB offers the benefits of an SQL database *and* the scalability and flexibility typically associated with NoSQL databases.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] Modest CrateDB clusters can ingest tens of thousands of records per second without breaking a sweat.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] You can run ad-hoc queries using standard SQL.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] CrateDB's blazing-fast distributed query execution engine parallelizes query workloads across the whole cluster.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] CrateDB is well suited to containerization, can be scaled horizontally using ephemeral virtual machines (e.g., Kubernetes, AWS, and Azure) with no shared state.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] You can deploy and run CrateDB on any sort of network — from personal computers to multi-region hybrid clouds and the edge.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] Or visit the installation documentation to see all the available download and install options.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] Once you're up and running, head over to the introductory docs.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] To interact with CrateDB, you can use the Admin UI sql console or the CrateDB shell CLI tool.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] Alternatively, review the list of recommended clients and tools that work with CrateDB.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] For container-specific documentation, check out the CrateDB on Docker how-to guide or the CrateDB on Kubernetes how-to guide.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] This project is primarily maintained by Crate.io, but we welcome community contributions!
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] See the developer docs and the contribution docs for more information.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] The CrateDB team and community take security bugs seriously.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] We appreciate your efforts to responsibly disclose your findings, and will make every effort to acknowledge your contributions.
[src:cratedb/blob-readme-rst] If you think you discovered a security flaw, please follow the guidelines at SECURITY.md.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:cratedb/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:cratedb/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:cratedb/guide] CrateDB is a fully open-source **distributed SQL database** designed for **real-time analytics, search and AI** at scale.
[src:cratedb/guide] Whether you are working with time series data, full-text search, or large volumes of structured and semi-structured data, CrateDB gives you the **power of SQL**, the **scalability of NoSQL**, and the **flexibility of a modern data platform**.
