[src:cratedb/reference-latest] This resource assumes you know the basics.
[src:cratedb/reference-latest] If not, check out the Tutorials section for beginner material.
[src:cratedb/reference-latest] CrateDB is an open source project and is hosted on GitHub.
[src:cratedb/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:cratedb/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:cratedb/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:cratedb/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:cratedb/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:cratedb/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:cratedb/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:cratedb/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:cratedb/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:cratedb/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:cratedb/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:cratedb/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:cratedb/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:cratedb/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:cratedb/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:cratedb/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:cratedb/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:cratedb/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:cratedb/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:cratedb/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:cratedb/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:cratedb/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:cratedb/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:cratedb/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:cratedb/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:cratedb/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:cratedb/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:cratedb/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:cratedb/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:cratedb/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:cratedb/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:cratedb/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:cratedb/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:cratedb/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:cratedb/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:cratedb/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:cratedb/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:cratedb/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:cratedb/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:cratedb/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:cratedb/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:cratedb/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:cratedb/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:cratedb/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:cratedb/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:cratedb/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:cratedb/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:cratedb/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:cratedb/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:cratedb/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:cratedb/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:cratedb/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:cratedb/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:cratedb/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:cratedb/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:cratedb/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:cratedb/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:cratedb/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:cratedb/sql] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:cratedb/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:cratedb/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:cratedb/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:cratedb/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:cratedb/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:cratedb/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:cratedb/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:cratedb/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:cratedb/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:cratedb/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:cratedb/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:cratedb/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:cratedb/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:cratedb/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
